The error you are seeing is due to the use of curly quotation marks (“ ”) instead of straight quotation marks (" ") in your code. Python expects standard ASCII quotation marks to enclose string literals.

Here's the corrected code snippet:

```python
# Function to run a shell command and display its output
def run_shell_command(cmd):
    try:
        output = subprocess.check_output(cmd, stderr=subprocess.STDOUT, shell=True, timeout=300, universal_newlines=True)
        print(output)
    except subprocess.CalledProcessError as e:
        print("An error occurred: {}".format(e.output))
    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:
        print("The command took too long to run and was terminated.")
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        print("The command was manually interrupted.")
```

Make sure to replace all curly quotation marks with the standard straight ones throughout your entire code to avoid similar syntax errors in the future.
